Next, we have a template for the submit page called submit.html. Here the user is able to submit a message to the message bank.
Here is the template for submit.html:

{% extends 'base.html' %}

{% block header %}
  &lt;h1 style="color: green; font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif; text-shadow: 2px 2px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5)"&gt;{% block title %}&lt;span class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;Submit a Message&lt;/span&gt;{% endblock %}&lt;/h1&gt;
{% endblock %}



{% block content %}

  &lt;style&gt;
    /* Import Google Fonts */
    @import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Protest+Guerrilla&display=swap');

    /* Apply custom font */
    .protest-guerrilla-regular {
      font-family: "Protest Guerrilla", sans-serif;
      font-weight: 400;
      font-style: normal;
    }

    /* Set background color */
    body {
      background-color:  #192841;
    }
  &lt;/style&gt;

  &lt;form method="post"&gt;
      &lt;label for="name" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;What's your name?&lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;input name="name" id="name" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;
      &lt;label for="message" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;What is your message?&lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;input type="text" name="message" id="message" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;
      &lt;input type="submit" value="Post Message" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;
  &lt;/form&gt;
  {% if sec == True %}
  &lt;br&gt;
      &lt;b&gt;Message sent&lt;/b&gt;
  {% endif %}
{% endblock %}

Again, some of this file is the style prefernces for the page. I choose to use a google api to get the Protest Guerrilla font for some of this page.
We can examine the most important part of the file below:

&lt;form method="post"&gt;
    &lt;label for="name" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;What's your name?&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;input name="name" id="name" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;
    &lt;label for="message" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;What is your message?&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="message" id="message" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;
    &lt;input type="submit" value="Post Message" class="protest-guerrilla-regular"&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;

We can see that there are two prompts for the user: “What’s your name?” and “What is your message?”. We can see that these are then called name and message respectively. So once the user submits their info the input_message function will be called and their info will be entered into the database.
The html page is also based on base.html as we include {% extends ‘base.html’ %} at the top of the page. Therefore the writing of the home page is still there and the prompts show up below.



Finally, we have our third template, view.html. This page will allow the user to view the random messages from the message bank.
Here is the implementation of the view.html template:

{% extends 'base.html' %}

{% block title %}
    Random Messages
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
    &lt;div class="container"&gt;
        &lt;h1&gt;Random Messages&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;ul&gt;
            {% for message in messages %}
                &lt;li&gt;
                    &lt;div class="message"&gt;
                        &lt;p&gt;{{ message[0] }}&lt;/p&gt; &lt;!-- name --&gt;
                        &lt;p&gt;{{ message[1] }}&lt;/p&gt; &lt;!-- message --&gt;
                    &lt;/div&gt;
                &lt;/li&gt;
            {% endfor %}
        &lt;/ul&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
{% endblock %}

{% block header %}
    &lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='view_style.css') }}"&gt;
{% endblock %}

As before, we still use base.html to extend this template and some the code is for styling. As I wanted this page to have its own style for the viewing of the message bank, I created a new file called view_style.css for the style of this page. We can take a look into the most imporant parts of the template.

&lt;div class="container"&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Random Messages&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;ul&gt;
        {% for message in messages %}
            &lt;li&gt;
                &lt;div class="message"&gt;
                    &lt;p&gt;{{ message[0] }}&lt;/p&gt; &lt;!-- name --&gt;
                    &lt;p&gt;{{ message[1] }}&lt;/p&gt; &lt;!-- message --&gt;
                &lt;/div&gt;
            &lt;/li&gt;
        {% endfor %}
    &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

We can see that we call the top of the page Random Messages. We then run a loop to go over all the individual messages in messages that we retrieved from our random_messages function. Then for each message we output the name and message, with indices of 0 and 1 respectively.
We can also look at the view_style.css page that was used for styling below:


        /* Additional styles specific to this template */
        .container {
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #333; /* Darker gray container background */
            border-radius: 10px; /* Rounded corners */
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5); /* Shadow effect */
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #ff5722; /* Orange color */
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            text-shadow: 2px 2px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
            font-size: 36px; /* Larger font size */
        }
        ul {
            list-style-type: none;
            padding: 0;
            margin: 0;
        }
        .message {
            background-color: #444; /* Dark gray message background */
            border-radius: 10px; /* Rounded corners */
            box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3); /* Shadow effect */
            padding: 20px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            transition: box-shadow 0.3s ease; /* Smooth transition */
        }
        .message:hover {
            box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5); /* Larger shadow on hover */
            transform: translateY(-5px); /* Move up slightly on hover */
        }
        p {
            color: #ccc; /* Light gray text */
            font-size: 18px; /* Medium font size */
            font-style: italic; /* Italic text */
            margin: 0; /* Remove default margin */
        }




Now that we have gone through the implementation on the webstie we can run through a quick demo of the site.
We will first look at the base page of the website:



Home Page of Message Bank


As we can “Welcome to the Message Bank!” is displayed at the top the site, followed by the description of what the site does.
Below the discription, we can see two different links to click: Post Messages and View Messages. These will allow the user to move to different parts of the site.
We can also see that there are no routes in the url so we are at the base page and the webpage is called Message Bank, as we can see on the tab.
As an example lets navigate to the Post Messages page and fill in an example posted message:



Submit Page of Message Bank


As we can see we have naviagted to the submit page of the website. We see that the /submit route is added to the URL. The user is now able to input their name and their message. We can also see some of the style changes, as the google api font is used in this section.
In this example, the name is Arvin (my name) and the message is that I love basketball.
We can then click the submit button and it would send this tuple to the database.
Finally we can look at the view page of the website. Let’s navigate to that:



View Page of Message Bank


As we can see we are now in the view page of the website. We see that the route has now changed from /submit to /view. We can also see that there is a box with five random messages from the databse. All the messages have the names and the personal message attached. We see that the message that we submitted in the last page appears here as well.



The files for this website are hosted on a github repository. The repository is public so people are able to pull the code and make some modifications if they were interested.
Here is the link to the repository for the project:
https://github.com/arvinhosseini/messagebank



Thank you for reading my post! I hope that you were able to learn a bit about web development with flask, using a database, and CSS styling!

